document_data.Personality:
{{Quote|Well, I wouldn't be surprised if all this storming isn't the work of the High Hand of the Lady, whose nose is out of joint again because no one will give him a title.|Rumor overheard in Arabel{{Cite dungeon/61/Storm Season|34}}}}

Although considered a wise leader, he was imperious, He was by all accounts a true zealot.{{Cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2005)/07-29 - Daramos Lauthyr}}

Daramos was willing to engage in cheap tricks and showmanship, such as hiring commoners to fill seats at his sermons, in order to appear more impressive to visiting dignitaries.

document_data.Relationships:
Despite heavy resistance to his positions within the Church of Tymora, few disputed his wisdom and preeminent status. Many Tymorans outright feared him and found him unsuitable as high priest, but at the same time they admired how he positively radiated with Tymora's favor. Nearly all his failures turned to successes, and he seemed to exude luck. His fellow clergy were generally happy to cooperate with him, or at least not actively hinder him. They figured his ambition would lead to his downfall eventually, thereby solving the "problem" of Daramos Lauthyr.{{Cite organized play/LC/Good Evening Ladies and Gentlemen|2}}

His subordinate, [[Doust Sulwood]], formerly the lord of [[Shadowdale]] was critical of Daramos's ambitions.

King [[Azoun Obarskyr IV|Azoun IV]] considered Daramos to be a fanatic who was more devoted to his ambitions than to his goddess&mdash;though not by much. The King knew how much power Daramos held in Arabel and was careful not to anger him.
